WEBVTT

1
00:00:13.973 --> 00:00:15.975
[intriguing music playing]

2
00:00:24.984 --> 00:00:28.862
[Ben] <i>Someone once asked me
what universe this was.</i>

3
00:00:28.863 --> 00:00:30.530
<i>A strange question that</i>

4
00:00:30.531 --> 00:00:32.949
<i>stuck with me all these years later.</i>

5
00:00:32.950 --> 00:00:34.534
<i>All I could say for sure</i>

6
00:00:34.535 --> 00:00:37.579
<i>was it was the only one I knew of.</i>

7
00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:40.040
<i>And that was as true then as it is now.</i>

8
00:00:42.084 --> 00:00:44.586
<i>Am I an extraordinary man?</i>

9
00:00:44.587 --> 00:00:46.171
<i>Yes.</i>

10
00:00:46.172 --> 00:00:47.839
<i>Am I an ordinary man?</i>

11
00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:49.257
<i>Yes.</i>

12
00:00:49.258 --> 00:00:51.551
<i>I'm both. I'm neither.</i>

13
00:00:51.552 --> 00:00:53.220
<i>But aren't we all?</i>

14
00:00:55.514 --> 00:00:57.016
<i>New York.</i>

15
00:00:59.894 --> 00:01:01.896
<i>I grew up in this city.</i>

16
00:01:03.397 --> 00:01:04.939
<i>- I learned to fight in this city.</i>
- [kids grunting]

17
00:01:04.940 --> 00:01:06.442
Get him!

18
00:01:07.777 --> 00:01:09.779
[Ben] <i>And I fell in love in this city.</i>

19
00:01:13.365 --> 00:01:15.367
<i>A mistake I'll never make again.</i>

20
00:01:18.621 --> 00:01:20.705
<i>I used to be The Spider.</i>

21
00:01:20.706 --> 00:01:22.791
<i>this city's hero.</i>

22
00:01:22.792 --> 00:01:24.000
<i>Always on guard.</i>

23
00:01:24.001 --> 00:01:26.879
<i>always ready to swoop in
and save the day.</i>

24
00:01:27.713 --> 00:01:28.839
[grunting]

25
00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:46.607
<i>That ended when Ruby died.</i>

26
00:01:58.786 --> 00:02:01.788
<i>We were going to be married in the spring.</i>

27
00:02:01.789 --> 00:02:04.582
<i>I even bought a ring to make it official.</i>

28
00:02:04.583 --> 00:02:07.837
<i>A ring I never had the chance to give her.</i>

29
00:02:16.095 --> 00:02:18.054
<i>Ruby once told me that</i>

30
00:02:18.055 --> 00:02:22.100
<i>with great power
comes great responsibility.</i>

31
00:02:22.101 --> 00:02:24.435
{\an8}<i>Well. she was the greatest responsibility</i>

32
00:02:24.436 --> 00:02:26.521
{\an8}<i>I ever had.</i>

33
00:02:26.522 --> 00:02:28.524
<i>And I failed her.</i>

34
00:02:30.234 --> 00:02:32.236
<i>The Spider failed her.</i>

35
00:02:35.531 --> 00:02:38.742
<i>After that. I didn't want
the power or the responsibility.</i>

36
00:02:42.746 --> 00:02:45.541
<i>So I went back to being
just an ordinary man.</i>

37
00:02:47.751 --> 00:02:50.129
<i>That was five years ago.</i>

38
00:02:55.384 --> 00:02:57.386
{\an8}[♪ Kirby sings "Saving Grace"]

39
00:03:04.727 --> 00:03:07.395
{\an8}<i>♪ The colors fading from the photograph ♪</i>

40
00:03:07.396 --> 00:03:09.147
<i>♪ I could tell the story ♪</i>

41
00:03:09.148 --> 00:03:11.816
<i>♪ but still you wouldn't know the half ♪</i>

42
00:03:11.817 --> 00:03:14.611
{\an8}<i>♪ This love was brought to life
from shards of glass ♪</i>

43
00:03:14.612 --> 00:03:16.696
{\an8}<i>♪ When you kiss me there's a shifting ♪</i>

44
00:03:16.697 --> 00:03:19.157
<i>♪ in the sepia tone ♪</i>

45
00:03:19.158 --> 00:03:22.368
{\an8}<i>♪ Can't escape the madness.
baby. magnetism ♪</i>

46
00:03:22.369 --> 00:03:25.705
{\an8}<i>♪ Run away but something
pulls me back into it ♪</i>

47
00:03:25.706 --> 00:03:28.833
{\an8}<i>♪ Lately I've been staring
at a broken mirror ♪</i>

48
00:03:28.834 --> 00:03:32.295
<i>♪ Needing someone to call my own ♪</i>

49
00:03:32.296 --> 00:03:35.506
<i>♪ Hey. lover ♪</i>

50
00:03:35.507 --> 00:03:38.384
{\an8}<i>♪ I need someone to save me now ♪</i>

51
00:03:38.385 --> 00:03:40.637
{\an8}<i>♪ from all the pain ♪</i>

52
00:03:40.638 --> 00:03:43.097
{\an8}<i>♪ I suffer ♪</i>

53
00:03:43.098 --> 00:03:45.934
{\an8}<i>♪ and the heavy world
that weighs me down ♪</i>

54
00:03:45.935 --> 00:03:49.479
{\an8}<i>♪ 'Cause the world ain't sweet ♪</i>

55
00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:51.856
{\an8}<i>♪ It's bitter to taste ♪</i>

56
00:03:51.857 --> 00:03:53.232
{\an8}<i>♪ But you could be ♪</i>

57
00:03:53.233 --> 00:03:56.445
<i>♪ my saving grace ♪</i>

58
00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:19.802
[song ends]

59
00:04:22.054 --> 00:04:24.138
- [piano playing up-tempo jazz]
- [match strikes]

60
00:04:24.139 --> 00:04:26.141
[quiet. indistinct chatter]

61
00:04:39.071 --> 00:04:40.572
What do you think?

62
00:04:45.119 --> 00:04:47.036
[woman] I think you got a bingo.

63
00:04:47.037 --> 00:04:48.955
Say. you're kinda handsome.

64
00:04:48.956 --> 00:04:50.707
Now I'm questioning your eyesight.

65
00:04:50.708 --> 00:04:51.791
[chuckles]

66
00:04:51.792 --> 00:04:53.126
Funny. too.

67
00:04:53.127 --> 00:04:55.378
So. you got a wife?

68
00:04:55.379 --> 00:04:57.714
- No.
- Shame.

69
00:04:57.715 --> 00:04:59.173
I got a husband.

70
00:04:59.174 --> 00:05:01.342
Not that it's ever stopped me
from having a good time.

71
00:05:01.343 --> 00:05:02.343
Know what I mean?

72
00:05:02.344 --> 00:05:04.429
I've got a decent idea.

73
00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:07.433
When your husband gets the same idea.
tell him to give me a call.

74
00:05:08.475 --> 00:05:10.102
[woman] Hm. Okay.

75
00:05:13.939 --> 00:05:15.607
[busboy] Excuse me. sir? Sir!

76
00:05:16.608 --> 00:05:17.775
You forgot your hat.

77
00:05:17.776 --> 00:05:19.069
Thank you.

78
00:05:20.154 --> 00:05:23.614
You keep following me.
it won't end the way you want it to.

79
00:05:23.615 --> 00:05:25.409
It never does.

80
00:05:27.077 --> 00:05:28.494
Addison!

81
00:05:28.495 --> 00:05:29.954
[cars honking]

82
00:05:29.955 --> 00:05:31.874
[thrilling music playing]

83
00:05:42.426 --> 00:05:43.385
[grunts]

84
00:05:49.475 --> 00:05:51.684
Sorry. pal. Hey.

85
00:05:51.685 --> 00:05:53.478
Don't do it. Addison.

86
00:05:53.479 --> 00:05:56.273
I'm as liable to shoot you
as I am to give chase.

87
00:05:59.151 --> 00:06:00.861
Damn it!

88
00:06:08.786 --> 00:06:10.203
[people chattering]

89
00:06:10.204 --> 00:06:11.830
[woman] Oh. my God. is he dead?

90
00:06:15.793 --> 00:06:17.294
- [gasps]
- [onlookers exclaim]

91
00:06:18.879 --> 00:06:20.755
- [grunts]
- Sir. sir. you shouldn't--

92
00:06:20.756 --> 00:06:22.925
- You really shouldn't--
- Where did they go? Which way?

93
00:06:49.827 --> 00:06:51.452
[high-pitched ringing]

94
00:06:51.453 --> 00:06:53.997
[distorted. muffled voice speaking]

95
00:06:58.127 --> 00:07:01.712
[man] It's not my fault you ripped off
the wrong people. Addison.

96
00:07:01.713 --> 00:07:05.133
Now. come on. let's go. It's getting late
and it smells like shit back here.

97
00:07:05.134 --> 00:07:06.802
I tried to warn you.

98
00:07:07.803 --> 00:07:09.304
What?

99
00:07:10.347 --> 00:07:11.306
Whoa.

100
00:07:17.729 --> 00:07:19.857
Now you're gonna burn.

101
00:07:27.906 --> 00:07:29.866
Jesus. Mary and Joseph.

102
00:07:29.867 --> 00:07:31.577
- [grunting]
- [whimpering]

103
00:07:35.622 --> 00:07:38.624
Oh… Oh. no. Oh. my God! Oh...

104
00:07:38.625 --> 00:07:41.003
Whoa. whoa! [grunts]

105
00:07:43.630 --> 00:07:45.132
[Ben grunting]

106
00:08:03.150 --> 00:08:04.610
Huh.

107
00:08:10.741 --> 00:08:12.617
Okay.

108
00:08:12.618 --> 00:08:16.162
[exclaims]
Oh! That man was completely on fire.

109
00:08:16.163 --> 00:08:18.164
I've never seen such a thing.

110
00:08:18.165 --> 00:08:20.833
Should've known it was fishy
they offered me 50 bucks

111
00:08:20.834 --> 00:08:22.001
to track down a nobody.

112
00:08:22.002 --> 00:08:24.212
Who hired you-- guy named Winston?

113
00:08:24.213 --> 00:08:26.715
- Yeah.
- Bastard only offered me 30.

114
00:08:28.675 --> 00:08:30.343
I need a drink. You?

115
00:08:30.344 --> 00:08:33.012
Sure. Nothing too fancy. All I got is--

116
00:08:33.013 --> 00:08:34.138
Three bucks.

117
00:08:34.139 --> 00:08:37.433
Come on. Donegal. I know a joint. [grunts]

118
00:08:37.434 --> 00:08:41.062
Might even have a girl for you.
If you like train wrecks.

119
00:08:41.063 --> 00:08:43.522
Oh. I must.

120
00:08:43.523 --> 00:08:45.525
'cause I keep marrying 'em.

121
00:08:51.073 --> 00:08:52.198
Morning.

122
00:08:52.199 --> 00:08:53.616
It was.

123
00:08:53.617 --> 00:08:55.785
Now it's a mediocre afternoon.
headed towards

124
00:08:55.786 --> 00:08:57.995
a lousy evening. Coffee?

125
00:08:57.996 --> 00:09:00.289
You got anything a little harder?

126
00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:02.124
That's what I keep asking my husband.

127
00:09:02.125 --> 00:09:04.252
- You can just pour it right in.
- That's just it--

128
00:09:04.253 --> 00:09:05.503
you really can't.

129
00:09:05.504 --> 00:09:06.796
- Any calls?
- Well. to receive calls.

130
00:09:06.797 --> 00:09:09.090
you got to pay Ma Bell.

131
00:09:09.091 --> 00:09:11.175
Till then. that's just a paperweight.

132
00:09:11.176 --> 00:09:12.469
How'd it go with Addison?

133
00:09:14.137 --> 00:09:16.139
Oh. wow. That well. huh?

134
00:09:17.766 --> 00:09:19.183
Addison's dead.

135
00:09:19.184 --> 00:09:20.393
- You...
- No.

136
00:09:20.394 --> 00:09:24.272
- Some other guy. This goddamn city--
- [door opens]

137
00:09:24.273 --> 00:09:25.523
You open?

138
00:09:25.524 --> 00:09:26.899
- No!
- Yes!

139
00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:28.401
I tried calling. but it didn't

140
00:09:28.402 --> 00:09:30.361
- seem to go through.
- Mr.-Mr. Reilly believes that

141
00:09:30.362 --> 00:09:32.363
business is better conducted face-to-face.

142
00:09:32.364 --> 00:09:34.615
Wouldn't you agree. Mister…?

143
00:09:34.616 --> 00:09:35.574
Uh. Carmedy.

144
00:09:35.575 --> 00:09:37.077
Right this way. Mr. Carmedy.

145
00:09:38.537 --> 00:09:39.871
It's about my wife.

146
00:09:50.841 --> 00:09:53.718
You a rich man. Mr. Carmedy?

147
00:09:53.719 --> 00:09:56.637
No. Not particularly.

148
00:09:56.638 --> 00:09:58.515
Possessed of a keen wit. then?

149
00:09:59.308 --> 00:10:00.309
Huh?

150
00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:02.643
Huh.

151
00:10:02.644 --> 00:10:04.937
Look. I heard my wife
on the phone this afternoon.

152
00:10:04.938 --> 00:10:07.815
She's gonna meet
this so-and-so at 8:00 tonight.

153
00:10:07.816 --> 00:10:10.276
I even got the address. Look. look. look.

154
00:10:10.277 --> 00:10:13.154
I do love a client who comes prepared.

155
00:10:13.155 --> 00:10:15.281
So you'll do it? You'll take the case?

156
00:10:15.282 --> 00:10:17.616
Okay. Carmedy.
my rate's ten dollars a day. plus--

157
00:10:17.617 --> 00:10:19.910
But you'll get pictures. right?

158
00:10:19.911 --> 00:10:23.331
Cause without pictures it's basically
just a-a "he said. she said" situation.

159
00:10:23.332 --> 00:10:25.958
I'm sure your suspicions are unfounded.
Mr. Carmedy.

160
00:10:25.959 --> 00:10:28.794
but if it comes to it. don't you fret.
Ben's an ace photographer.

161
00:10:28.795 --> 00:10:29.713
Never miss a shot.

162
00:10:32.424 --> 00:10:34.008
Ten dollars a day.

163
00:10:34.009 --> 00:10:35.676
Plus expenses.

164
00:10:35.677 --> 00:10:38.220
Janet'll get your info
and a small retainer.

165
00:10:38.221 --> 00:10:40.848
Come back day after tomorrow
and. uh… [clears throat]

166
00:10:40.849 --> 00:10:41.974
I'll give you what you want.

167
00:10:41.975 --> 00:10:44.518
[exclaims softly] Thank you. [chuckles]

168
00:10:44.519 --> 00:10:45.728
[chuckles softly] Come on. Mr. Carmedy.

169
00:10:45.729 --> 00:10:47.021
let's get that info
and that retainer. huh?

170
00:10:47.022 --> 00:10:48.981
[Carmedy laughs]

171
00:10:48.982 --> 00:10:50.484
[quirky music playing]

172
00:10:51.568 --> 00:10:55.237
Explosion at Standard Oil.
Read all about it.

173
00:10:55.238 --> 00:10:58.532
Explosion at Standard Oil.

174
00:10:58.533 --> 00:11:02.329
Explosion. here. at Standard Oil.

175
00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:17.635
- [entry bells jingle]
- [door closes]

176
00:11:17.636 --> 00:11:20.054
Sorry I'm late. I was chasing a story.

177
00:11:20.055 --> 00:11:21.430
Some other mobster

178
00:11:21.431 --> 00:11:24.934
is finally making a move on Silvermane.

179
00:11:24.935 --> 00:11:26.852
Burned down his mansion
a couple of nights ago.

180
00:11:26.853 --> 00:11:28.354
killed six of his men.

181
00:11:28.355 --> 00:11:31.107
and somehow.
the old bastard escaped.

182
00:11:31.108 --> 00:11:33.526
You think Finn Byrne
likes being called Silvermane?

183
00:11:33.527 --> 00:11:36.862
Thinks it speaks to-- I don't know--
gravitas and longevity?

184
00:11:36.863 --> 00:11:39.365
[short chuckle]
If I ever get that rich. you call me

185
00:11:39.366 --> 00:11:41.952
- anything you want.
- That-That's a used pickle. Uh...

186
00:11:43.537 --> 00:11:45.288
So. what you hiding over there--
another cheating spouse?

187
00:11:48.417 --> 00:11:49.708
Thought you said you weren't gonna
take those anymore.

188
00:11:49.709 --> 00:11:52.545
I haven't paid Janet in months.
Beggars can't be choosers.

189
00:11:52.546 --> 00:11:56.382
Says the man who has chosen
to be a beggar. For Chrissakes. Ben--

190
00:11:56.383 --> 00:11:58.301
Robbie. not today. okay? Not again.

191
00:12:00.178 --> 00:12:01.887
Have you seen it out there?

192
00:12:01.888 --> 00:12:03.472
The city's a mess.

193
00:12:03.473 --> 00:12:05.558
Ever since The Spider disappeared.

194
00:12:05.559 --> 00:12:08.144
Silvermane's got this city by the throat.

195
00:12:08.145 --> 00:12:09.728
Crime is out of control

196
00:12:09.729 --> 00:12:12.481
and the police
are completely in his pocket.

197
00:12:12.482 --> 00:12:13.774
Now. the people--

198
00:12:13.775 --> 00:12:16.361
the people could use a hero.

199
00:12:19.823 --> 00:12:21.574
Well...

200
00:12:21.575 --> 00:12:23.284
I hope they find someone.

201
00:12:23.285 --> 00:12:26.121
- You used to be--
- I know who I used to be.

202
00:12:28.665 --> 00:12:31.625
And I know who I am now.

203
00:12:31.626 --> 00:12:34.587
There's always gonna
be another Silvermane. Robbie.

204
00:12:34.588 --> 00:12:36.047
There's no point in fighting it.

205
00:12:37.090 --> 00:12:40.134
I can't help but wonder what Ruby would
think if she heard you talking like that.

206
00:12:40.135 --> 00:12:41.469
[dramatic music playing]

207
00:12:41.470 --> 00:12:43.430
[muffled grunting]

208
00:12:53.273 --> 00:12:55.275
Ruby's been dead a long time.

209
00:12:57.360 --> 00:12:59.529
I don't care what she'd think anymore.

210
00:13:06.077 --> 00:13:08.078
Hey. Frankie. you're out early today.

211
00:13:08.079 --> 00:13:10.832
Hey. Reilly. how you doing?

212
00:13:13.877 --> 00:13:16.128
You know. I've been
practicing my pocket tricks.

213
00:13:16.129 --> 00:13:18.256
[Ben] Oh. yeah? How's that going?

214
00:13:19.674 --> 00:13:22.135
[Frankie] You tell me. [wolf whistles]

215
00:13:24.763 --> 00:13:25.930
Dames. huh?

216
00:13:25.931 --> 00:13:27.097
What would you know?

217
00:13:27.098 --> 00:13:29.099
Lots. I'm wise behind these ears.

218
00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:31.060
Smarts like that.
maybe think about going to school.

219
00:13:31.061 --> 00:13:33.604
Who needs it? A plus B equals C.

220
00:13:33.605 --> 00:13:35.689
- You don't do math with letters. kid.
- [line ringing]

221
00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:37.233
Donegal. Reilly.

222
00:13:37.234 --> 00:13:39.528
Listen. I think we should
talk about last night.

223
00:13:40.779 --> 00:13:43.197
[Donegal] <i>So. what's this proposition
you got for me?</i>

224
00:13:43.198 --> 00:13:45.157
We left a man dead last night.

225
00:13:45.158 --> 00:13:47.409
Feels like that could be trouble
coming down the tracks

226
00:13:47.410 --> 00:13:50.246
or an opportunity worth pursuing.
Either way.

227
00:13:50.247 --> 00:13:52.039
I think we should know more
about who hired us

228
00:13:52.040 --> 00:13:54.084
and why they wanted him so bad.

229
00:13:57.170 --> 00:13:58.296
So you got a plan. then?

230
00:13:59.381 --> 00:14:02.508
Kinda.
Can you be sober by 9:00 a.m. tomorrow?

231
00:14:02.509 --> 00:14:05.804
Oh. hi. handsome. Long time no see.

232
00:14:07.097 --> 00:14:08.514
By the morning?

233
00:14:08.515 --> 00:14:10.058
Mm... sure.

234
00:14:11.768 --> 00:14:13.269
[newsie shouting] <i>Get your
evening edition.</i>

235
00:14:13.270 --> 00:14:15.896
Silvermane survives in skivvies.

236
00:14:15.897 --> 00:14:17.398
Thank you. sir.

237
00:14:17.399 --> 00:14:19.567
Hot off the presses.

238
00:14:19.568 --> 00:14:22.027
<i>Silvermane survives in skivvies.</i>

239
00:14:22.028 --> 00:14:24.071
[Robbie] <i>Ever since
The Spider disappeared.</i>

240
00:14:24.072 --> 00:14:26.949
<i>Silvermane has had
a chokehold on this city.</i>

241
00:14:26.950 --> 00:14:29.827
<i>murdering anyone that gets in his way.</i>

242
00:14:29.828 --> 00:14:32.288
<i>But one brave soul tried to free us</i>

243
00:14:32.289 --> 00:14:34.331
<i>from the mobster's reign of terror.</i>

244
00:14:34.332 --> 00:14:36.375
<i>setting fire to Silvermane's mansion</i>

245
00:14:36.376 --> 00:14:38.669
<i>while he was asleep upstairs.</i>

246
00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:40.796
<i>But he failed to kill the old bastard.</i>

247
00:14:40.797 --> 00:14:43.048
<i>so brace yourself for a bloody rampage</i>

248
00:14:43.049 --> 00:14:45.384
<i>from Silvermane and his goons.</i>

249
00:14:45.385 --> 00:14:47.553
<i>If only The Spider were here</i>

250
00:14:47.554 --> 00:14:49.513
<i>to save us from the madness.</i>

251
00:14:49.514 --> 00:14:51.682
Damn. Robbie.

252
00:14:51.683 --> 00:14:53.685
Give it a rest. would you?

253
00:14:58.523 --> 00:15:00.525
[contemplative music playing]

254
00:15:12.787 --> 00:15:14.789
♪ ♪

255
00:15:32.807 --> 00:15:35.225
Evening. sir. How can I help you?

256
00:15:35.226 --> 00:15:38.020
I got a delivery for Boris Karloff.

257
00:15:38.021 --> 00:15:40.022
[doorman] Sorry. bud.
Karloff don't live here.

258
00:15:40.023 --> 00:15:43.192
[Ben] No. sure he does.
He might be listed under his stage name.

259
00:15:43.193 --> 00:15:44.861
Uh. Stein.

260
00:15:45.987 --> 00:15:49.449
Frank N. Stein.

261
00:15:50.659 --> 00:15:51.867
[elevator bell dings]

262
00:15:51.868 --> 00:15:54.913
All right. Don't bother.
I'll see myself out.

263
00:16:07.050 --> 00:16:08.551
[sighs]

264
00:16:10.929 --> 00:16:12.513
[grunts]

265
00:16:12.514 --> 00:16:14.516
[panting]

266
00:16:26.069 --> 00:16:28.071
[grunting]

267
00:16:30.115 --> 00:16:32.200
[grunting]

268
00:16:39.833 --> 00:16:42.252
[man chuckling inside]

269
00:16:45.964 --> 00:16:47.966
[indistinct conversation]

270
00:17:10.321 --> 00:17:11.447
[woman] No. stop.

271
00:17:11.448 --> 00:17:13.574
- [man] Come on... Come on.
- No.

272
00:17:13.575 --> 00:17:14.616
[man] Gimme something.

273
00:17:14.617 --> 00:17:16.660
[woman] Get off of me!

274
00:17:16.661 --> 00:17:18.287
[man] Come here!

275
00:17:18.288 --> 00:17:19.621
[kissing]

276
00:17:19.622 --> 00:17:20.915
- [grunts]
- Oh!

277
00:17:21.958 --> 00:17:22.792
[thwip]

278
00:17:24.294 --> 00:17:26.004
What the hell?

279
00:17:42.771 --> 00:17:44.104
He's here early.

280
00:17:44.105 --> 00:17:45.939
[whispering] You're late.

281
00:17:45.940 --> 00:17:47.901
Go. Go.

282
00:17:50.445 --> 00:17:52.029
Morning. Winston.

283
00:17:52.030 --> 00:17:54.406
Care for a cup of coffee
or maybe some tea

284
00:17:54.407 --> 00:17:57.367
or do you just want to order both
and see which one comes first?

285
00:17:57.368 --> 00:17:59.119
Save your breath. Reilly.

286
00:17:59.120 --> 00:18:00.704
You told me you know where Addison is.

287
00:18:00.705 --> 00:18:02.664
so take your money and talk.

288
00:18:02.665 --> 00:18:04.917
Actually. the price has gone up.

289
00:18:04.918 --> 00:18:06.252
Excuse me?

290
00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:09.797
The other PI you hired
told me offered him 50.

291
00:18:09.798 --> 00:18:12.508
so I'm not telling you
for a penny less than 200.

292
00:18:12.509 --> 00:18:14.843
Cute.

293
00:18:14.844 --> 00:18:16.887
But give me one good reason
I shouldn't plug you.

294
00:18:16.888 --> 00:18:18.972
[suspenseful music playing]

295
00:18:18.973 --> 00:18:20.390
How about 38 reasons?

296
00:18:20.391 --> 00:18:22.267
- [gun cocks]
- It's actually a .32.

297
00:18:22.268 --> 00:18:25.103
but I doubt your organs
will know the difference.

298
00:18:25.104 --> 00:18:27.940
Now. a guy like you in a suit like that--

299
00:18:27.941 --> 00:18:30.400
you didn't cook this up on your own.

300
00:18:30.401 --> 00:18:33.570
So. why don't you go back
to whoever it is that sent you

301
00:18:33.571 --> 00:18:34.988
and find me 200 dollars.

302
00:18:34.989 --> 00:18:36.865
And then I'll tell you where Addison is.

303
00:18:36.866 --> 00:18:39.743
- And I'll keep the .30 as a tip.
- [clears throat]

304
00:18:39.744 --> 00:18:42.538
Janet'll keep the .30 as a tip.

305
00:18:42.539 --> 00:18:43.873
Cute.

306
00:18:45.124 --> 00:18:46.376
Real cute.

307
00:18:57.929 --> 00:18:59.931
[engine starts]

308
00:19:10.233 --> 00:19:12.235
♪ ♪

309
00:19:36.467 --> 00:19:38.469
♪ ♪

310
00:19:53.234 --> 00:19:55.110
[soft chuckle]

311
00:19:55.111 --> 00:19:56.695
Funny.

312
00:19:56.696 --> 00:19:58.864
Guy burns down my house.

313
00:19:58.865 --> 00:20:00.908
tries to kill me...

314
00:20:00.909 --> 00:20:02.660
Makes me feel young again.

315
00:20:03.828 --> 00:20:06.246
Did Reilly tell you where Addison is?

316
00:20:06.247 --> 00:20:07.873
[Winston] A shakedown.

317
00:20:07.874 --> 00:20:11.043
He won't tell me where Addison is
unless he gets more cash.

318
00:20:11.044 --> 00:20:12.420
[Silvermane] Pay him whatever he wants.

319
00:20:13.504 --> 00:20:16.716
The boys are convinced
Addison's got some kind of powers.

320
00:20:21.012 --> 00:20:23.847
If he does. I want to talk to him.

321
00:20:23.848 --> 00:20:25.474
Do whatever it takes.

322
00:20:25.475 --> 00:20:27.143
Find Addison.

323
00:20:33.733 --> 00:20:35.777
Hot damn! Can you believe our luck?

324
00:20:36.861 --> 00:20:39.905
Sadly. yes.
Stepping into a steaming pile of dogshit

325
00:20:39.906 --> 00:20:41.740
is kind of my specialty.

326
00:20:41.741 --> 00:20:44.368
Are you daft?
Byrne's the deepest pockets in New York.

327
00:20:44.369 --> 00:20:46.203
We're the only ones
who know Addison's dead.

328
00:20:46.204 --> 00:20:47.621
We can ask for a thousand now.

329
00:20:47.622 --> 00:20:49.748
Shake down Silvermane? It's an idea.

330
00:20:49.749 --> 00:20:52.876
Thing is. I've got
this crazy preference for being alive.

331
00:20:52.877 --> 00:20:54.962
You do what you want.
I'm leaving this one alone.

332
00:20:54.963 --> 00:20:58.590
You're a coward. Reilly.
Fortune favors the bold.

333
00:20:58.591 --> 00:21:00.510
- And look how poor I am.
- [laughs]

334
00:21:05.556 --> 00:21:07.141
[Janet in distance] I'm in here.

335
00:21:08.434 --> 00:21:09.518
[door opens]

336
00:21:09.519 --> 00:21:10.727
How'd that go?

337
00:21:10.728 --> 00:21:12.229
- [Ben] Dead end.
- [door closes]

338
00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:13.438
How about this?

339
00:21:13.439 --> 00:21:15.983
[clicks tongue] Uh... interesting.

340
00:21:15.984 --> 00:21:17.067
You got some great shots.

341
00:21:17.068 --> 00:21:19.487
- [Ben chuckles] I couldn't resist.
- [chuckles]

342
00:21:20.947 --> 00:21:22.739
I do have one question. though.

343
00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:25.659
Am I crazy or is that
the goddamn mayor of New York?

344
00:21:25.660 --> 00:21:28.954
[ominous music playing]

345
00:21:28.955 --> 00:21:31.206
[mayor over speakers] <i>I believe in you.</i>

346
00:21:31.207 --> 00:21:34.001
<i>the hardworking man
trying to earn a decent living.</i>

347
00:21:34.002 --> 00:21:37.546
<i>I believe in you. the dedicated woman.</i>

348
00:21:37.547 --> 00:21:40.340
<i>Our city has hit hard times.</i>

349
00:21:40.341 --> 00:21:42.217
<i>We've lost our heroes.</i>

350
00:21:42.218 --> 00:21:44.886
<i>It feels like no one is coming to help us.</i>

351
00:21:44.887 --> 00:21:47.764
<i>But I believe we can
be our own heroes. together.</i>

352
00:21:47.765 --> 00:21:49.933
[Carmedy] You sure
she didn't meet up with anybody?

353
00:21:49.934 --> 00:21:52.436
Like I said. your... wife

354
00:21:52.437 --> 00:21:54.604
was alone the entire night.

355
00:21:54.605 --> 00:21:57.816
What about 8:00 p.m.? The-the Redcliff?
What was that all about?

356
00:21:57.817 --> 00:22:00.110
Come on. Carmedy. smile.
This is great news.

357
00:22:00.111 --> 00:22:02.821
- No. I-I know. I know. I just...
- I get it.

358
00:22:02.822 --> 00:22:04.740
- Marriage can be a terrifying endeavor.
- Oh...

359
00:22:04.741 --> 00:22:07.117
opening yourself up
to another person like that.

360
00:22:07.118 --> 00:22:08.660
making yourself vulnerable.

361
00:22:08.661 --> 00:22:10.454
I don't even feel good
about taking your money.

362
00:22:10.455 --> 00:22:11.872
- [Carmedy] Really?
- Yeah.

363
00:22:11.873 --> 00:22:14.583
Go home. Carmedy.
You have a beautiful…[laughs]

364
00:22:14.584 --> 00:22:16.418
- and loyal wife.
- Oh.

365
00:22:16.419 --> 00:22:19.004
You know how loyal she is.

366
00:22:19.005 --> 00:22:21.131
- I-I...
- You're a very lucky man.

367
00:22:21.132 --> 00:22:22.632
- Yeah?
- Now go home.

368
00:22:22.633 --> 00:22:24.384
[chuckles weakly] Uh...

369
00:22:24.385 --> 00:22:26.636
- [door closes]
- We needed that money.

370
00:22:26.637 --> 00:22:30.140
I don't know if you're aware.
but there's a Depression going on.

371
00:22:30.141 --> 00:22:33.226
I'm aware. but whatever that was.
I want nothing to do with it.

372
00:22:33.227 --> 00:22:34.227
Who do you think he was?

373
00:22:34.228 --> 00:22:36.313
Who knows?
Someone trying to smear the mayor.

374
00:22:36.314 --> 00:22:38.398
And that woman--
if she's not Mrs. Carmedy.

375
00:22:38.399 --> 00:22:40.150
then who the hell is she?

376
00:22:40.151 --> 00:22:41.735
The only thing I can say
with any certainty

377
00:22:41.736 --> 00:22:44.488
is she isn't married
to that syphilitic walrus.

378
00:22:44.489 --> 00:22:46.073
[groans]

379
00:22:46.074 --> 00:22:48.493
[muffled pulsing. warbling]

380
00:22:51.704 --> 00:22:54.624
Another headache. huh?
That sixth sense thing?

381
00:22:55.541 --> 00:22:57.125
You should listen to it.

382
00:22:57.126 --> 00:22:58.835
Long as I've known you
it's never steered you wrong.

383
00:22:58.836 --> 00:23:01.964
I'd love to. Trouble is I'm not currently
sure what it's trying to tell me.

384
00:23:02.673 --> 00:23:03.716
Hang on.

385
00:23:04.801 --> 00:23:06.052
Oh. I can hear it.

386
00:23:06.928 --> 00:23:08.261
It's saying...

387
00:23:08.262 --> 00:23:11.139
"Pay your secretary." Except you can't.

388
00:23:11.140 --> 00:23:13.391
'cause you just gave away the only money
we've made all month.

389
00:23:13.392 --> 00:23:14.309
You're at the top of my list.

390
00:23:14.310 --> 00:23:16.812
Yeah. well. you better
do something about it soon.

391
00:23:16.813 --> 00:23:19.272
I just interviewed
for a sales position at Gimbels.

392
00:23:19.273 --> 00:23:22.025
Blame my husband.
He has this annoying habit

393
00:23:22.026 --> 00:23:24.237
of demanding food on a daily basis.

394
00:23:27.824 --> 00:23:30.450
What about selling the photographs
to the woman?

395
00:23:30.451 --> 00:23:32.494
You want to steer clear of the mayor.
that's fine.

396
00:23:32.495 --> 00:23:35.455
but maybe
there's still some cash to be had.

397
00:23:35.456 --> 00:23:36.957
[mischievous music playing]

398
00:23:36.958 --> 00:23:39.251
Blackmail. huh?

399
00:23:39.252 --> 00:23:40.836
That's not a terrible idea.

400
00:23:40.837 --> 00:23:42.379
- It's not a good idea.
- Ah.

401
00:23:42.380 --> 00:23:44.131
but it's not a terrible idea.

402
00:23:44.132 --> 00:23:46.049
[Robbie] <i>Yeah. I shit you not.</i>

403
00:23:46.050 --> 00:23:47.926
she had me covered in whipped cream
all the way up to here.

404
00:23:47.927 --> 00:23:51.930
[chuckles] Girl. Robbie'll do anything
to get the story.

405
00:23:51.931 --> 00:23:54.224
Jesus. you look like shit.

406
00:23:54.225 --> 00:23:55.600
More than usual. is what I'm saying.

407
00:23:55.601 --> 00:23:57.853
- Nice to see you. too.
- [Robbie] <i>What's so important</i>

408
00:23:57.854 --> 00:23:59.604
it couldn't wait
till I was back downtown?

409
00:23:59.605 --> 00:24:01.607
Any chance you know who this is?

410
00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:04.943
[Robbie] Ah. you must be joking.

411
00:24:04.944 --> 00:24:06.278
Oh. that's Cat Hardy.

412
00:24:06.279 --> 00:24:08.573
Back in the day.
you wouldn't have had to ask.

413
00:24:10.867 --> 00:24:12.869
Five minutes. Drawer three.

414
00:24:15.788 --> 00:24:17.455
What are you looking for. anyway?

415
00:24:17.456 --> 00:24:20.667
Uh. some poor sap
got knocked off a few nights ago.

416
00:24:20.668 --> 00:24:23.336
Friend gave me a tip
something's off with the body.

417
00:24:23.337 --> 00:24:24.839
Might be a story in it.

418
00:24:26.924 --> 00:24:29.134
Say. uh. you might want to look away.

419
00:24:29.135 --> 00:24:32.220
Any idea where I can find
this Cat Hardy lady?

420
00:24:32.221 --> 00:24:33.930
[Robbie] Oh. yeah.

421
00:24:33.931 --> 00:24:36.851
Now. she is the star attraction
over at The Alcove.

422
00:24:39.145 --> 00:24:42.190
Huh. That is weird.

423
00:24:43.482 --> 00:24:46.319
Say. does this look like
a guy who died in a fire to you?

424
00:24:47.778 --> 00:24:50.990
[Ben] No. but he sure as hell did.
I was there.

425
00:24:52.491 --> 00:24:53.450
And?

426
00:24:53.451 --> 00:24:55.285
They ID him yet?

427
00:24:55.286 --> 00:24:56.745
[Robbie] James Addison.

428
00:24:56.746 --> 00:24:58.705
Shit.

429
00:24:58.706 --> 00:25:00.123
So. if they know. the cops'll know.

430
00:25:00.124 --> 00:25:03.168
and then Silvermane will know
that Donegal is trying to rip him off.

431
00:25:03.169 --> 00:25:05.378
Do me a favor. Hold off on printing that.

432
00:25:05.379 --> 00:25:07.881
I want to warn a friend
before he gets himself killed.

433
00:25:07.882 --> 00:25:09.258
[groans]

434
00:25:09.926 --> 00:25:12.761
What? It's just a migraine. [groans]

435
00:25:12.762 --> 00:25:14.138
[muffled pulsing. warbling]

436
00:25:15.181 --> 00:25:16.348
[groans]

437
00:25:16.349 --> 00:25:18.558
[foreboding music playing]

438
00:25:18.559 --> 00:25:20.352
What's going on. Ben?

439
00:25:20.353 --> 00:25:21.854
Did this guy have super powers?

440
00:25:25.608 --> 00:25:26.901
Is he like you?

441
00:25:27.985 --> 00:25:31.197
Forget about it. Robbie. He's dead.

442
00:25:33.532 --> 00:25:35.242
<i>Did Donegal say when he'd be back?</i>

443
00:25:35.243 --> 00:25:36.660
[bartender] <i>He didn't say shit.</i>

444
00:25:36.661 --> 00:25:39.287
That's what I told the other fellas
and that's what I'm telling you.

445
00:25:39.288 --> 00:25:43.041
If he comes in. tell him to meet
Ben Reilly at The Alcove. 9:00 p.m.

446
00:25:43.042 --> 00:25:44.376
Tell him it's important.

447
00:25:44.377 --> 00:25:46.379
[upbeat jazz music playing]

448
00:25:59.684 --> 00:26:01.686
- [piano playing gentle jazz music]
- [indistinct chatter]

449
00:26:08.609 --> 00:26:10.611
Old Fashioned.

450
00:26:22.623 --> 00:26:24.125
[scoffs quietly]

451
00:26:28.713 --> 00:26:30.338
[emcee] Ladies and gentlemen.

452
00:26:30.339 --> 00:26:32.090
Cat Hardy.

453
00:26:32.091 --> 00:26:33.592
[applause]

454
00:26:38.806 --> 00:26:43.351
[Cat] <i>♪ Stars shining bright ♪</i>

455
00:26:43.352 --> 00:26:46.605
<i>♪ above you ♪</i>

456
00:26:47.982 --> 00:26:51.277
<i>♪ Night breezes seem to ♪</i>

457
00:26:52.820 --> 00:26:56.490
<i>♪ whisper. "I love you" ♪</i>

458
00:26:57.783 --> 00:27:00.118
<i>♪ Birds singing ♪</i>

459
00:27:00.119 --> 00:27:03.706
<i>♪ in the sycamore trees ♪</i>

460
00:27:06.375 --> 00:27:09.503
<i>♪ Dream a little dream ♪</i>

461
00:27:11.088 --> 00:27:14.382
<i>♪ of me... ♪</i>

462
00:27:14.383 --> 00:27:16.385
[band begins playing
"Dream a Little Dream of Me"]

463
00:27:17.470 --> 00:27:19.346
<i>♪ Say "Nighty-night" ♪</i>

464
00:27:19.347 --> 00:27:23.141
<i>♪ and kiss me ♪</i>

465
00:27:23.142 --> 00:27:24.642
<i>♪ Just hold me tight ♪</i>

466
00:27:24.643 --> 00:27:28.105
<i>♪ and tell me you'll miss me ♪</i>

467
00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:30.940
<i>♪ While I'm alone ♪</i>

468
00:27:30.941 --> 00:27:33.943
<i>♪ and blue as can be ♪</i>

469
00:27:33.944 --> 00:27:36.112
<i>♪ Dream a little dream ♪</i>

470
00:27:36.113 --> 00:27:39.866
<i>♪ of me ♪</i>

471
00:27:39.867 --> 00:27:41.618
<i>♪ Sweet dreams ♪</i>

472
00:27:41.619 --> 00:27:44.871
<i>♪ till sunbeams find you ♪</i>

473
00:27:44.872 --> 00:27:47.374
<i>♪ Sweet dreams that leave ♪</i>

474
00:27:47.375 --> 00:27:49.959
<i>♪ all worries behind you ♪</i>

475
00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:52.504
<i>♪ But in your dreams ♪</i>

476
00:27:52.505 --> 00:27:55.048
<i>♪ whatever they be ♪</i>

477
00:27:55.049 --> 00:27:57.008
<i>♪ Dream a little dream ♪</i>

478
00:27:57.009 --> 00:28:01.012
<i>♪ of me ♪</i>

479
00:28:01.013 --> 00:28:03.473
<i>♪ Quarter past ten and we're laughing ♪</i>

480
00:28:03.474 --> 00:28:05.892
<i>♪ It's the past tense of a daydream ♪</i>

481
00:28:05.893 --> 00:28:08.061
<i>♪ We'll go dancing under lights dim ♪</i>

482
00:28:08.062 --> 00:28:10.313
<i>♪ and it's past tense
when we say things ♪</i>

483
00:28:10.314 --> 00:28:12.774
<i>♪ From the dead of night
till the morning dew ♪</i>

484
00:28:12.775 --> 00:28:15.068
<i>♪ From the black and white
to the colorful ♪</i>

485
00:28:15.069 --> 00:28:17.070
<i>♪ If I'm not there. my belle ♪</i>

486
00:28:17.071 --> 00:28:19.656
<i>♪ dream me in a bow. make it beautiful ♪</i>

487
00:28:19.657 --> 00:28:22.867
<i>♪ We've been swimming ♪</i>

488
00:28:22.868 --> 00:28:28.081
<i>♪ in the usual ♪</i>

489
00:28:28.082 --> 00:28:32.043
<i>♪ but this deluge ♪</i>

490
00:28:32.044 --> 00:28:36.756
<i>♪ is delusional ♪</i>

491
00:28:36.757 --> 00:28:41.177
<i>♪ Dream of me. dream of me ♪</i>

492
00:28:41.178 --> 00:28:45.432
<i>♪ till I'm everything you see ♪</i>

493
00:28:45.433 --> 00:28:48.518
<i>♪ Dream of me ♪</i>

494
00:28:48.519 --> 00:28:53.189
<i>♪ dream of me till it's reality ♪</i>

495
00:28:53.190 --> 00:28:55.567
<i>♪ Don't dream too big ♪</i>

496
00:28:55.568 --> 00:28:59.863
<i>♪ just dream a little dream of me ♪</i>

497
00:28:59.864 --> 00:29:01.698
- [high-pitched ringing]
- <i>♪ I want you to dream ♪</i>

498
00:29:01.699 --> 00:29:03.658
<i>♪ a little dream of me ♪</i>

499
00:29:03.659 --> 00:29:07.036
<i>♪ Just a little tiny dream ♪</i>

500
00:29:07.037 --> 00:29:09.998
<i>♪ A little dream ♪</i>

501
00:29:09.999 --> 00:29:14.086
<i>♪ of me... ♪</i>

502
00:29:20.092 --> 00:29:22.136
- [applause]
- [man whoops]

503
00:29:23.846 --> 00:29:25.848
[band playing gentle jazz]

504
00:29:31.312 --> 00:29:33.314
[menacing music playing]

505
00:29:35.274 --> 00:29:36.692
[coin rattles]

506
00:29:38.527 --> 00:29:40.529
[line ringing]

507
00:29:41.655 --> 00:29:45.450
Damn it. Donegal. Where the hell are you?

508
00:29:45.451 --> 00:29:46.952
[Silvermane] Wake him up.

509
00:29:48.245 --> 00:29:49.747
Um...

510
00:29:51.707 --> 00:29:53.417
...that ain't gonna be so easy.

511
00:29:55.169 --> 00:29:56.670
He's dead.

512
00:29:58.172 --> 00:29:59.923
[Pudge] Told you I had a killer right.

513
00:29:59.924 --> 00:30:01.425
[giggles]

514
00:30:11.018 --> 00:30:13.770
[Donegal whimpers]

515
00:30:13.771 --> 00:30:15.439
Sorry. boss.

516
00:30:20.945 --> 00:30:22.487
Evening. friend.

517
00:30:22.488 --> 00:30:25.740
I'm not interested
in revenge or retribution.

518
00:30:25.741 --> 00:30:29.327
So I'm going to make this quick. Okay?

519
00:30:29.328 --> 00:30:31.330
[crying softly]

520
00:30:32.831 --> 00:30:35.833
Now. now. there's nothing to cry about.

521
00:30:35.834 --> 00:30:39.672
I'd just like to hear where Addison is.

522
00:30:43.092 --> 00:30:44.260
Do you know?

523
00:30:46.720 --> 00:30:48.680
Do you know?

524
00:30:48.681 --> 00:30:51.975
Uh. I shot him dead.

525
00:30:51.976 --> 00:30:55.186
He had some kind of crazy powers.

526
00:30:55.187 --> 00:30:57.981
- He burst into flames.
- [Silvermane] And what about

527
00:30:57.982 --> 00:31:01.110
the name of the man
who hired Addison to kill me?

528
00:31:02.486 --> 00:31:04.237
[whimpering] I. uh...

529
00:31:04.238 --> 00:31:06.114
I don't know.

530
00:31:06.115 --> 00:31:07.324
Fair enough.

531
00:31:11.620 --> 00:31:13.830
It's all over.

532
00:31:13.831 --> 00:31:15.540
It's done.

533
00:31:15.541 --> 00:31:17.834
[Donegal wheezes]

534
00:31:17.835 --> 00:31:19.545
[coughs]

535
00:31:32.308 --> 00:31:33.600
[Silvermane] Go to the morgue.

536
00:31:33.601 --> 00:31:35.644
Make sure Addison is really dead.

537
00:31:37.021 --> 00:31:38.855
And bring me the other private dick.

538
00:31:38.856 --> 00:31:41.399
Reilly?
He don't know any more than this guy.

539
00:31:41.400 --> 00:31:44.278
[Silvermane] Then he's got
nothing to worry about then. does he?

540
00:31:47.364 --> 00:31:49.366
- [indistinct chatter]
- [band playing gentle jazz]

541
00:31:56.206 --> 00:31:57.416
Do you mind?

542
00:31:58.500 --> 00:31:59.835
Please.

543
00:32:01.587 --> 00:32:03.671
I loved your performance.

544
00:32:03.672 --> 00:32:05.340
Thanks. doll.

545
00:32:05.341 --> 00:32:07.383
Is there somewhere we can talk?

546
00:32:07.384 --> 00:32:08.718
Here suits me.

547
00:32:08.719 --> 00:32:10.219
It's business.

548
00:32:10.220 --> 00:32:12.722
I wasn't aware we had any. Mister…?

549
00:32:12.723 --> 00:32:13.848
Reilly.

550
00:32:13.849 --> 00:32:16.476
It concerns your trip
to The Redcliff last night.

551
00:32:16.477 --> 00:32:17.894
Flint.

552
00:32:17.895 --> 00:32:20.521
Wh-- Now. I-I'm trying to help you.

553
00:32:20.522 --> 00:32:21.564
- I--
- [low growl]

554
00:32:21.565 --> 00:32:24.108
Mr. Reilly. I'd like you
to meet my friend. Flint Marko.

555
00:32:24.109 --> 00:32:26.110
- He's--
- A gorilla?

556
00:32:26.111 --> 00:32:27.820
Do you mind?

557
00:32:27.821 --> 00:32:31.074
- Slowly.
- Oh. the ape speaks. Incredible.

558
00:32:31.075 --> 00:32:32.910
I thought you might find that useful.

559
00:32:34.411 --> 00:32:36.579
- Everything. okay. Ms. Hardy?
- Yes.

560
00:32:36.580 --> 00:32:39.540
Mr. Reilly's a very nice man.
but he was just about to leave.

561
00:32:39.541 --> 00:32:41.584
- Who told you that?
- That you were leaving?

562
00:32:41.585 --> 00:32:44.087
- That I'm nice.
- Just a hunch.

563
00:32:44.088 --> 00:32:46.547
Maybe you can confirm it by leaving
without messing up Flint's tie.

564
00:32:46.548 --> 00:32:49.884
He really struggles with a double Windsor
and I just painted my nails.

565
00:32:49.885 --> 00:32:51.387
Sharpened 'em. too.

566
00:32:52.346 --> 00:32:53.846
And don't trouble yourself. Flint.

567
00:32:53.847 --> 00:32:56.849
I'm happy to make my exit
without either of your fists

568
00:32:56.850 --> 00:32:58.559
busting my eye sockets.

569
00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:01.145
Um. take another look at that
and perhaps tomorrow

570
00:33:01.146 --> 00:33:02.980
we can discuss the price of the negatives

571
00:33:02.981 --> 00:33:05.358
over lunch. I might even pay.

572
00:33:05.359 --> 00:33:08.569
seeing as I'm such a nice guy.

573
00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:10.446
I suppose you think you're pretty clever.

574
00:33:10.447 --> 00:33:12.448
No. actually. most days
I think I should just

575
00:33:12.449 --> 00:33:14.575
stick my head in the oven
and get it over with.

576
00:33:14.576 --> 00:33:15.576
Well. what's stopping you?

577
00:33:15.577 --> 00:33:17.329
Simple. I'm a coward.

578
00:33:25.754 --> 00:33:27.756
[tense music playing]

579
00:33:32.428 --> 00:33:34.887
Spare some change for a hungry orphan boy?

580
00:33:34.888 --> 00:33:37.098
I got to tail? White suit?

581
00:33:37.099 --> 00:33:39.518
Sure do. mister. Thanks.

582
00:34:01.457 --> 00:34:03.459
♪ ♪

583
00:34:20.726 --> 00:34:22.895
♪ ♪

584
00:34:42.498 --> 00:34:44.665
[Ben] Some view up here.

585
00:34:44.666 --> 00:34:47.210
You can see the lights
all the way from Jersey.

586
00:34:47.211 --> 00:34:49.378
[Flint] I'd like those negatives. please.

587
00:34:49.379 --> 00:34:51.006
[Ben] Cutting right to it. huh?

588
00:34:53.342 --> 00:34:55.177
You don't even want to catch your breath?

589
00:34:56.178 --> 00:34:58.721
Mister. despite what I do for a living.

590
00:34:58.722 --> 00:35:00.890
I really don't enjoy hurting people.

591
00:35:00.891 --> 00:35:02.558
Then don't.

592
00:35:02.559 --> 00:35:05.228
I know a terrific hamburger joint.
open all night.

593
00:35:05.229 --> 00:35:06.814
Let's sit. Talk it over.

594
00:35:08.315 --> 00:35:11.234
So you're not hungry. How about a drink?

595
00:35:11.235 --> 00:35:12.860
Last chance.

596
00:35:12.861 --> 00:35:14.570
Opium?

597
00:35:14.571 --> 00:35:15.489
[grunting]

598
00:35:20.077 --> 00:35:21.661
Why be stubborn?

599
00:35:21.662 --> 00:35:24.914
One way or another.
you're gonna give me those negatives.

600
00:35:24.915 --> 00:35:28.252
- It doesn't have to be like this.
- You're right. You could stop punching me.

601
00:35:30.879 --> 00:35:33.131
The negatives or I drop you.

602
00:35:36.969 --> 00:35:38.636
[chuckles] Well. the thing is...

603
00:35:38.637 --> 00:35:40.346
I'm not really scared of heights.

604
00:35:40.347 --> 00:35:41.640
[both grunting]

605
00:36:10.669 --> 00:36:12.170
[panting]

606
00:36:16.508 --> 00:36:17.925
[Flint grunting]

607
00:36:17.926 --> 00:36:19.594
[soft crumpling. shifting]

608
00:36:19.595 --> 00:36:21.597
[eerie music playing]

609
00:36:34.776 --> 00:36:36.861
Jesus...

610
00:36:36.862 --> 00:36:38.488
[grunting continuing]

611
00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:46.537
Flint?

612
00:36:46.538 --> 00:36:48.540
[grunting continuing]

613
00:37:02.012 --> 00:37:04.014
[low growling]

614
00:37:18.695 --> 00:37:20.780
[propulsive music playing]

615
00:37:20.781 --> 00:37:22.199
[grunting]

616
00:38:06.994 --> 00:38:08.286
[Ben grunts]

617
00:38:09.621 --> 00:38:11.164
[yelling]

618
00:38:14.960 --> 00:38:15.836
[sharp exhale]

619
00:38:16.962 --> 00:38:18.338
[grunting]

620
00:38:26.888 --> 00:38:28.890
[lift gears squeaking]

621
00:38:30.017 --> 00:38:31.267
[lift door opens]

622
00:38:31.268 --> 00:38:32.769
[Cat] Don't hurt him.

623
00:38:34.896 --> 00:38:37.356
- Where am I? Huh?
- Flint?

624
00:38:37.357 --> 00:38:39.233
Are you okay?

625
00:38:39.234 --> 00:38:40.736
What happened?

626
00:38:42.404 --> 00:38:44.196
What the hell is this?

627
00:38:44.197 --> 00:38:46.700
Just leave us alone. please.

628
00:38:51.121 --> 00:38:53.915
Here are the negatives. On the house.

629
00:38:58.378 --> 00:39:00.380
[plaintive music playing]

630
00:39:05.886 --> 00:39:06.969
[Janet] <i>I can't</i>

631
00:39:06.970 --> 00:39:10.514
believe you gave her the negatives.
And for free.

632
00:39:10.515 --> 00:39:11.849
Don't you think you're overreacting?

633
00:39:11.850 --> 00:39:13.184
No. Ben. [short chuckle]

634
00:39:13.185 --> 00:39:14.852
This is what reacting looks like.

635
00:39:14.853 --> 00:39:16.896
It's the physical response to a stimulus.

636
00:39:16.897 --> 00:39:19.315
You just haven't felt it in half a decade.

637
00:39:19.316 --> 00:39:22.193
That's actually my lamp.
My-my... my aunt gave it to me.

638
00:39:22.194 --> 00:39:23.444
You're afraid of the mob-- sure.

639
00:39:23.445 --> 00:39:25.237
Don't want to piss off the mayor-- fine.

640
00:39:25.238 --> 00:39:27.323
But a lounge singer?

641
00:39:27.324 --> 00:39:29.992
I told you. there were
extenuating circumstances.

642
00:39:29.993 --> 00:39:31.702
I have given you so much room.

643
00:39:31.703 --> 00:39:33.412
Airplanes have less runway.

644
00:39:33.413 --> 00:39:35.873
But at a certain point.
when someone tells you what they are.

645
00:39:35.874 --> 00:39:37.083
you have to listen.

646
00:39:37.084 --> 00:39:38.834
[Cat] And what is he?

647
00:39:38.835 --> 00:39:40.628
[sultry music playing]

648
00:39:40.629 --> 00:39:41.630
Retired.

649
00:39:43.507 --> 00:39:45.174
Cat Hardy.

650
00:39:45.175 --> 00:39:47.718
Uh. meet my secretary. Janet Ruiz.

651
00:39:47.719 --> 00:39:49.513
Ex-secretary. I just quit.

652
00:39:50.347 --> 00:39:53.183
Shame. I came here to offer him a job.

653
00:39:55.310 --> 00:39:56.644
My friend Flint--

654
00:39:56.645 --> 00:39:58.562
the one you met last night--

655
00:39:58.563 --> 00:40:00.357
he's disappeared.

656
00:40:02.109 --> 00:40:03.609
Fifty dollar retainer. up front.

657
00:40:03.610 --> 00:40:05.112
Then it's ten a day. plus expenses.

658
00:40:14.454 --> 00:40:16.456
[propulsive music playing]

659
00:40:18.416 --> 00:40:19.668
[grunts]

660
00:40:20.669 --> 00:40:23.338
My friend Flint--
the one you met last night?

661
00:40:24.256 --> 00:40:25.256
[grunts]

662
00:40:25.257 --> 00:40:26.340
[Cat] <i>He's disappeared.</i>

663
00:40:26.341 --> 00:40:27.508
[Flint panting]

664
00:40:27.509 --> 00:40:28.551
[Janet] <i>He turned into sand.</i>

665
00:40:28.552 --> 00:40:30.804
right?
Just seems like. kind of like a big deal.

666
00:40:32.430 --> 00:40:34.140
[Cat] <i>You're an investigator.</i>

667
00:40:34.141 --> 00:40:35.392
Investigate.

668
00:40:40.689 --> 00:40:42.189
[Janet] <i>She is hiding something.</i>

669
00:40:42.190 --> 00:40:44.860
You know. sometimes I think
you forget I do this for a living.

670
00:40:46.987 --> 00:40:48.279
- [The Spider] Oh. come on.
- [grunts]

671
00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:49.488
What the hell is going on?

672
00:40:49.489 --> 00:40:51.323
[Ben] <i>I can't get into it right now.</i>

673
00:40:51.324 --> 00:40:54.577
[Robbie] <i>Suddenly you're not the only guy
in New York with powers.</i>

674
00:40:54.578 --> 00:40:56.537
<i>and you can't get into it right now?</i>

675
00:40:56.538 --> 00:40:59.332
[Silvermane] <i>The Spider appears
to have forgotten who runs this town.</i>

676
00:41:00.292 --> 00:41:01.458
We've got a fight coming.

677
00:41:01.459 --> 00:41:03.044
I want you to help me.

678
00:41:03.753 --> 00:41:05.922
<i>We have a man nobody can stop.</i>

679
00:41:07.632 --> 00:41:09.258
[Leyden] <i>It's the best damn show</i>

680
00:41:09.259 --> 00:41:10.635
in town.

681
00:41:16.099 --> 00:41:18.225
- [bartender] <i>What about The Spider?</i>
- [man 1] <i>The Spider?</i>

682
00:41:18.226 --> 00:41:19.560
- [men laughing]
- [man 2] Yeah. right.

683
00:41:19.561 --> 00:41:22.438
Look. maybe... maybe. maybe. maybe

684
00:41:22.439 --> 00:41:24.773
The Spider is a guy like anyone else.

685
00:41:24.774 --> 00:41:26.359
You ever think about that?

686
00:41:30.405 --> 00:41:31.947
[Morris] <i>Crime is out of control.</i>

687
00:41:31.948 --> 00:41:33.490
<i>The city needs order.</i>

688
00:41:33.491 --> 00:41:34.701
[Robbie] <i>You have a choice.</i>

689
00:41:35.368 --> 00:41:36.745
You just have to make it.

690
00:41:39.664 --> 00:41:41.249
[grunting]

691
00:41:44.252 --> 00:41:46.755
[The Spider chuckles] Ah-cha-cha! Ha.

692
00:41:47.839 --> 00:41:49.715
Did you see that?

693
00:41:49.716 --> 00:41:52.343
I kicked them into kingdom co... [coughs]

694
00:41:52.344 --> 00:41:54.178
♪ ♪

695
00:41:54.179 --> 00:41:55.222
[gunfire]

696
00:41:56.264 --> 00:41:58.432
- [screaming]
- [grunting]

697
00:41:58.433 --> 00:42:01.561
[Ben] <i>This is a part of me
I wish never existed.</i>

698
00:42:04.773 --> 00:42:06.607
<i>Because with no power</i>

699
00:42:06.608 --> 00:42:08.610
<i>comes no responsibility.</i>

700
00:42:11.404 --> 00:42:13.406
[intriguing music playing]

701
00:42:42.352 --> 00:42:44.354
♪ ♪

702
00:43:12.382 --> 00:43:14.384
♪ ♪

703
00:43:42.412 --> 00:43:44.414
♪ ♪

704
00:44:12.442 --> 00:44:14.444
♪ ♪
